    <center><table class="itemDisplayTable">
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Title:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Process Development, Optimization and Quality Evaluation of Nutraceutical and Functional Foods from Amla (Embilica Officinalis)</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Authors:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">G. Nagamaniammai</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Keywords:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Process Development, Optimization<br />Nutraceutical and Functional Foods from Amla (Embilica Officinalis)</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Issue Date:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Nov-2013 </td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Publisher:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Srm university</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Series/Report no.:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">T0145</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Abstract:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">This work titled “Process development, optimization and quality evaluation of Nutraceutical and Functional foods from amla (Embilica officinalis)” was carried out to develop two products namely (i) osmotically dehydrated amla pieces with spices and (ii) amla residue incorporated bread by keeping the beneficial effect of amla intact after processing. Amla (Emblica Officinalis Gaertn.) is rich in vitamin C and total polyphenols. Due to high acidity and astringency it is not considered as a common table fruit, moreover the fruit is perishable. Both the products developed in this work were studied at each stages of processing to assess the effectiveness of the process to retain the health beneficial compounds.
The first part of the work was to prepare amla pieces with spices. Hence the value added spices incorporated amla pieces were developed to increase the shelf-life and to have high consumer acceptability. The optimization of osmotic dehydration process of aonla slices in brine solution containing spices (cumin powder, fenugreek powder and fresh ginger extract) was carried out using response surface methodology; the experiments were conducted according to Box-Behnken design. The independent process variables for osmotic dehydration were salt concentration (4-12%) w/v, spices concentration (3-9%) w/v, solution to fruit ratio (3-5) v/w and duration (60-90min) at room temperature. The osmotic drying process was optimized for maximum water loss, solute gain, overall acceptability, minimum percentage acidity and vitamin C loss. The optimum conditions were 12% salt concentration, 7.09% spices concentration, 4.30 (v/w) solutions to fruit ratio, and 84.15min of process time. An analysis of variance (ANOVA) revealed that, among the process variables, salt concentration, process duration and spices concentration had maximum significant effect on water loss, solute gain, acidity and overall acceptability; process time has effect on vitamin C loss and acidity whereas solution-to-fruit ratio observed lesser significant effect on all the responses. The osmotic dehydration of aonla slices was carried out at the optimum conditions, the partially dehydrated aonla slices were dried in a tray drier and freeze drier to 15±1% moisture content. The freeze dried sample retained more vitamin C (0.443%), phenolic compounds (0.146%), tannin (0.203%) as well as higher ash content (2.01%)</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">URI:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue"><a href="http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/17327">http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/17327</a></td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Appears in Collections:</td><td class="metadataFieldValue"><a href="/dspace/handle/123456789/6855">Ph.D - Thesis  </a><br/></td></tr>
</table></center><br/>
